1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,680
 So now I want to show you another example of many-to-many

2
00:00:02,680 --> 00:00:04,880
 from an application that's near and dear to my heart

3
00:00:04,880 --> 00:00:06,600
 and that's the autograder that I use

4
00:00:06,600 --> 00:00:09,200
 for most of my online classes.

5
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:11,880
 So one of the things the autograder has to know

6
00:00:11,880 --> 00:00:14,660
 is like who is in what course

7
00:00:14,660 --> 00:00:18,320
 so that we can track grades based on people and courses.

8
00:00:18,320 --> 00:00:20,680
 And so this is the data model

9
00:00:20,680 --> 00:00:22,720
 and it's a little bit different syntax.

10
00:00:22,720 --> 00:00:24,200
 You sort of see one-to-many.

11
00:00:24,200 --> 00:00:26,760
 It's using what's called crow's feet

12
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:28,360
 and you see this little crow foot

13
00:00:28,360 --> 00:00:31,080
 and that's like a many when it sort of spreads out

14
00:00:31,080 --> 00:00:33,120
 and then you sort of have this one

15
00:00:33,120 --> 00:00:34,880
 and there's various little ways

16
00:00:34,880 --> 00:00:37,800
 and one or more or zero or more

17
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:40,560
 and so there's little, it's called a crow's foot diagram.

18
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:43,920
 But these diagrams ultimately are capturing the same thing

19
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:45,680
 whether these relationships are many-to-many

20
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:47,700
 or one-to-many and what the cardinality

21
00:00:47,700 --> 00:00:49,540
 of each end of the relationship is.

22
00:00:49,540 --> 00:00:52,200
 And this is showing a person table,

23
00:00:52,200 --> 00:00:55,280
 a course table and a membership table

24
00:00:55,280 --> 00:00:58,240
 and this is a very common thing that we have to solve

25
00:00:58,240 --> 00:01:01,680
 in educational systems and it's a little bit

26
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:04,040
 more sophisticated than the previous one

27
00:01:04,040 --> 00:01:06,080
 which I thought was beautifully elegant and simple

28
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:08,040
 but I wanna show you this one as well.

29
00:01:08,040 --> 00:01:11,520
 And so what we have here is basically

30
00:01:11,520 --> 00:01:16,360
 a people are in courses, right?

31
00:01:16,360 --> 00:01:17,880
 A person can be in many courses

32
00:01:17,880 --> 00:01:19,080
 and a course can have many people

33
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:21,080
 so it's a many-to-many relationship.

34
00:01:21,080 --> 00:01:22,120
 We create a through table.

35
00:01:22,120 --> 00:01:24,040
 We'll call it a member table.

36
00:01:24,040 --> 00:01:29,040
 We end up just like before with two one-to-many's pointing out

37
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:30,860
 or many-to-ones pointing outwards

38
00:01:30,860 --> 00:01:34,720
 so we have a person ID and a course ID in the member table.

39
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:37,280
 All three of these tables have primary keys

40
00:01:37,280 --> 00:01:41,360
 of ID, ID and ID and then we put the little tiny

41
00:01:41,360 --> 00:01:45,380
 sort of virtual set in here so that at a person

42
00:01:45,380 --> 00:01:47,960
 you can just look at a virtual set of their courses

43
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:51,380
 and of course you can say who are the members of this course.

44
00:01:52,660 --> 00:01:53,960
 Now we're gonna do one more thing

45
00:01:53,960 --> 00:01:55,220
 that's a little bit different here

46
00:01:55,220 --> 00:01:58,940
 and that is often the simplest of through tables

47
00:01:58,940 --> 00:02:03,060
 is literally an ID and two foreign keys.

48
00:02:03,060 --> 00:02:04,880
 And as a matter of fact, some people,

49
00:02:04,880 --> 00:02:06,160
 Django doesn't like doing this

50
00:02:06,160 --> 00:02:09,120
 but some people don't even include the ID field

51
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:10,840
 and they just make the combination

52
00:02:10,840 --> 00:02:14,560
 of the two foreign keys as a unique ID inside.

53
00:02:14,560 --> 00:02:16,040
 And if you're doing databases directly

54
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:17,420
 you can actually do that.

55
00:02:17,420 --> 00:02:20,620
 But here's a thing that you can also do.

56
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:23,840
 So if you think about in a teaching and learning situation

57
00:02:23,840 --> 00:02:26,760
 people aren't just members of courses.

58
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:28,840
 They are members of courses and they have a role

59
00:02:28,840 --> 00:02:32,400
 and is that role as a learner, a teaching assistant

60
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:34,000
 or an instructor or perhaps

61
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,340
 they're the departmental administrator, right?

62
00:02:36,340 --> 00:02:41,340
 And that is an attribute of the connection, right?

63
00:02:41,340 --> 00:02:44,200
 The connection between a person and a course

64
00:02:44,200 --> 00:02:47,320
 is the membership and oh by the way

65
00:02:47,320 --> 00:02:48,820
 they're not just a member,

66
00:02:48,820 --> 00:02:52,000
 they're a member with some metadata, okay?

67
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,780
 And so sometimes we add data to the through table

68
00:02:54,780 --> 00:02:56,480
 and it's actually quite useful

69
00:02:56,480 --> 00:02:59,440
 and it's really the only place to model this kind of data

70
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:03,100
 because somebody might be in a course as a teacher

71
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:05,380
 and they might be in a different course as a student

72
00:03:05,380 --> 00:03:07,940
 so you can't just say this person is always a teacher

73
00:03:07,940 --> 00:03:10,040
 or they're always a student, you can't say that.

74
00:03:10,040 --> 00:03:12,560
 It depends on the context and so that's why

75
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:15,040
 at the connection between a particular person

76
00:03:15,040 --> 00:03:17,880
 and a particular course we actually model

77
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:21,020
 the role that they have in that course.

78
00:03:21,020 --> 00:03:23,480
 So here we go.

79
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:26,880
 So we're going to have a person in a course

80
00:03:26,880 --> 00:03:32,800
 and we're going to have a through table, a membership

